  "text": "where || · || p denotes the l p norm, and (x, θ ) is the decision rule by the NN with parameters θ evaluated at x. The final constraint is somewhat arbitrary: it means that the adversarial example still belongs to the same space as the legitimate data point. Most current attacks are based on the gradient of a neural network s loss function: White-box attacks use the target NN to compute the gradient; Black-box attacks use a surrogate network to approximate the gradient. We will be using Fast Gradient Sign Method (FGSM) [CITATION_1] to illustrate our ideas. This attack takes the sign of the gradient and moves the data point x one step in that direction (see Figure 3 (A)):",
